Analysis for CHI 2025 submission.

Libraries and data.

outvis <- read.csv("Version 5 of Dataset Outviz - Sheet1-espbCoding.csv")

colnames(outvis)[8] ="Story_Generation"
colnames(outvis)[9] ="Story_Type"
colnames(outvis)[10] ="Enthusiasm"
colnames(outvis)[11] ="Preferred"
colnames(outvis)[12] ="Reason"
colnames(outvis)[13] ="Suggestion"

outvis$Questions[outvis$Questions == 0] <- "No question asked"
outvis$Questions[outvis$Questions == 2] <- "Statement includes a question"
# Participants only ever answered questions with the first condition they saw, so answering questions isn't terribly informative. So we'll recode the question-answering to be just "No question asked".
outvis$Questions[outvis$Questions == 1] <- "No question asked"

#outvis$Viz <- factor(outvis$Viz)
outvis$Questions <- factor(outvis$Questions)
outvis$Sufficiency <- factor(outvis$Sufficiency)
outvis$Story_Generation <- factor(outvis$Story_Generation)
outvis$Story_Type <- factor(outvis$Story_Type)
outvis$Enthusiasm <- factor(outvis$Enthusiasm)
outvis$Preferred <- factor(outvis$Preferred)
outvis$Reason <- factor(outvis$Reason)
outvis$Suggestion <- factor(outvis$Suggestion)

Recoding Preferred

The coding for Preferred includes statements that the participant preferred the current version (Preferred == 3) and that the participant preferred the other version (Preferred == 2). This makes the analysis both lower powered (because there are fewer observations of each type) and a bit confusing to interpret (if the participant preferred not this version, which one did they prefer?).

Lets try recoding to change the condition for just that statement. That is, if the participant said that they prefer the other version that they saw (Preferred == 2), then lets change it to saying that they prefer the current version (Preferred == 3) but change the condition (polr vs DBSCAN, and Polished vs Sketchy).


outvis$Model <- ifelse(outvis$Preferred == 2, ifelse(outvis$Model == "polr", "DBSCAN", "polr"), outvis$Model)
outvis$Viz <- ifelse(outvis$Preferred == 2, ifelse(outvis$Viz == "Sketchy", "Polished", "Sketchy"), outvis$Viz)

# Now that we've swapped the condition labels, adjust the Preferred coding accordingly.
outvis$Preferred[outvis$Preferred == 2] <- 3
outvis$Preferred <- droplevels(outvis$Preferred)

Combo Cond

Create a new variable that captures which of the 2x2 conditions from which each statement came. Then relevel combo.cond so that polr-Sketchy is the reference level. Also reorder levels to be more logical.

outvis$combo.cond <- as.factor(paste(outvis$Model, outvis$Viz, sep="-"))
outvis$combo.order <- paste(outvis$combo.cond, outvis$Order, sep="_") # this creates another variable that captures both the condition and the order in which each participant saw each condition

outvis$combo.cond <- factor(outvis$combo.cond, level = c("polr-Sketchy", "polr-Polished", "DBSCAN-Sketchy", "DBSCAN-Polished"))

Create a new variable that collapses all codes into a single variable.

NB: This code block currently generates an error, but code.and.value is no longer needed for the analysis.

# extract just the coded names for convenience
codes.df <- outvis[,6:13]

outvis$code.and.value <- as.factor(paste(outvis$applied.code, outvis$value.code, sep="_"))

Recoding Variables

Some of the variables we decided to recode for the CHI 2025 analysis. We can decide later exactly how to name them, but here is the general approach for what to do with the 8 coded variables.

  • Questions: Keep as is. - Suggestions: Collapse the two Suggestions codes into one, and rename it Suggesting a Change.
  • Preferred: Keep as is. Participants were explicitly asked which version they preferred, and this code indicates which of the two versions they saw that they preferred.
  • Reason: Collapse the two levels into a single code. This code essentially captures if/when participants provided detailed explanations justifying (i.e., giving reasons for) their preference.
  • Augmenting: Collapse into Task-Oriented feedback.
  • Story Generation: Collapse into Task-Oriented feedback.
  • Final Story Pitch: Collapse into Task-Oriented feedback.
  • Enthusiasm: Keep as is. Participants were explicitly asked how excited they would be. This isnt necessarily spontaneous feedback (like Questions and Suggestions would be). However, its still helpful to know whether they were enthused about the work that they did. Furthermore, verbalizing enthusiasm is different from verbalizing about the task itself.
outvis.recode <- outvis

# Collapse Suggestions
outvis.recode$Suggestion <- outvis.recode$Suggestion != 0

# Collapse Reason
outvis.recode$Reason <- outvis.recode$Reason != 0

# Combine task-oriented feedback into a single code
outvis.recode$Task_Oriented <- outvis.recode$Sufficiency != 0 | outvis.recode$Story_Generation != 0 | outvis.recode$Story_Type != 0

Multinomial logistic regression

Previous Version(s)

This is the model that Eric thinks makes the most sense to use (with polr_sketchy set as the reference level for combo.cond).

NB: Removing Enthusiasm=1 and Reason=1 has relatively little impact on the results. The one major difference is that, after this removal, Story_Generation=1 becomes significant for polr_concrete (rather than only being near significant before the removal).

outvis.relevel <- outvis

outvis.relevel <- within(outvis.relevel, combo.cond <- relevel(combo.cond, ref="polr-Sketchy"))

outvis.relevel$Enthusiasm[outvis.relevel$Enthusiasm == 1] <- 0
outvis.relevel$Enthusiasm <- droplevels(outvis.relevel$Enthusiasm)

outvis.relevel$Reason[outvis.relevel$Reason == 1] <- 0
outvis.relevel$Reason <- droplevels(outvis.relevel$Reason)

# epsb: reorganized these predictors to go in the same order as the RQs for our paper
combo.model <- multinom(combo.cond ~ Questions + Preferred + Enthusiasm + Sufficiency + Story_Generation + Story_Type + Suggestion + Reason, data = outvis.relevel)
# RQ1 (Perceived Usability): Questions, Preferred, Enthusiasm
# RQ2 (Task Completion): Sufficiency, Story_Generation, Story_Type
# RQ3 (Feedback): Suggestion, Reason

z <- summary(combo.model)$coefficients/summary(combo.model)$standard.errors
p <- (1 - pnorm(abs(z), 0, 1))*2
print(p)
print(exp(coef(combo.model)))

Highlights:

  • Questions were more likely to be asked by participants (Questions=2) with polr_concrete than with polr_sketchy (OR=2.65, p=0.027).
  • Final story pitches (Story_Generation=1) were less likely to be made using polr_sketchy more likely to be made using dbscan_concrete (OR=3.18, p=0.032), dbscan_sketchy (OR=2.40, p=0.093), or polr_concrete (OR=2.63, p=0.055). That last one is most interesting, because it suggests that the model itself wasnt necessarily holding people back from reaching a final story pitch, neither was the visualization holding people back, but rather there was something about the sketchy visualization combined with the polr model.
  • Statements about a participants preference being based on the visualization (Reason=2) were less likely from polr_sketchy and more likely from dbscan_concrete (OR=6.49, p=0.026), from dbscan_sketchy (OR=5.18, p=0.046), or from polr_concrete (OR=5.75, p=0.030). Again, interaction effect.
  • Near signif: Consulting Google or outside sources (Sufficiency=2) was more likely to occur with dbscan_concrete than with polr_sketchy (OR=7.38, p=0.081).
  • Near signif: Stories involving attributes of the business (Story_Type=1) were more common with polr_concrete than with polr_sketchy (OR=3.32, p=0.087).
  • Near signif: High enthusiasm was less common for polr_sketchy and more common for everything else: dbscan_concrete (OR=4.64, p=0.079), dbscan_sketchy (OR=4.53, p=0.070), and polr_concrete (OR=4.03, p=0.094). Again, this shows that theres an interaction, that the difference is neither the model alone nor the rendering style alone.

Revisions for CHI 2025

As before, well remove Enthusiasm == 1.

Well also remove Preferred == 1, since that only occurred once in the whole data set.

outvis.recode$Enthusiasm[outvis.recode$Enthusiasm == 1] <- 0
outvis.recode$Enthusiasm <- droplevels(outvis.recode$Enthusiasm)

outvis.recode$Preferred[outvis.recode$Preferred == 1] <- 0
outvis.recode$Preferred <- droplevels(outvis.recode$Preferred)

# epsb: Just putting these into task-oriented feedback first followed by all the design-oriented feedback.

Highlights:

  • Questions are significantly more likely to come from the polr-Polished condition (p=0.039, OR=2.60).
  • Suggestions are significantly less likely to come from the polr-Polished condition (p=0.025, OR=0.40).
  • No one prefers the polr-Sketchy version. Both p-value and OR are wildly inflated (due to lack of any statements where Preferred == 3 with polr-Sktechy).
  • Statements including a Reasons for the participants preference were less likely to come from polr-Sketchy (p-value from 0.046 to 0.10, OR from 5.21 to 3.84). Perhaps this result provides further evidence for our disengagement explanation with the polr-Sketchy condition. That is, not only did participants not like polr-Sketchy, they couldnt even be bothered to explain why they didnt like it (though we need to be cautious here the Preferred statements were in some cases expressed for a different condition, and I think some of those included Reason statements, too).
  • Statements involving Task-Oriented comments were more likely to come from the polr-Polished condition (p=0.026, OR=1.84) or the DBSCAN-Sketchy condition (p=0.049, OR=1.75) than from the polr-Sketchy condition. Initially, one could interpret this consistently with our disengagement explanation. However, its a bit surprising that the result does not follow a similar trend for DBSCAN-Polished. The qualitative analysis should probably look into the kinds of task oriented statements participants were making
  • Slightly less enthusiasm about the task (i.e., the story they generated) with polr-Sketchy than with DBSCAN-Sketchy p=0.97, OR=3.92). Id suggest this result, despite the somewhat large effect size, isnt worth spending much time on discussing or interpreting.

Effects Plots

Here, you should manually set model.to.plot as the model for which you want to generate effects plots.

NB: This cell will error if you try to run it with the model from the CHI 2025 revisions, because the model includes

model.to.plot <- combo.model
Error: object 'combo.model' not found

CHI 2025

Since we have different predictors for this analysis, we need different effects plots.

model.to.plot <- model.recode

eff.to.plot <- allEffects(model.to.plot)
plot(eff.to.plot, 'Questions', rug=FALSE, style="stacked", xlab="Participant asks a question", ylab="Probabilities for Each Condition")

plot(eff.to.plot, 'Suggestion', rug=FALSE, style="stacked", xlab="Participant makes a suggestion to improve the system", ylab="Probabilities for Each Condition")

plot(eff.to.plot, 'Preferred', rug=FALSE, style="stacked", xlab="Participant expresses a preference between two system variants", ylab="Probabilities for Each Condition")

plot(eff.to.plot, 'Reason', rug=FALSE, style="stacked", xlab="Participant's reason for their preferred variant", ylab="Probabilities for Each Condition")

plot(eff.to.plot, 'Task_Oriented', rug=FALSE, style="stacked", xlab="Participant makes a statement related to completing ", ylab="Probabilities for Each Condition")

plot(eff.to.plot, 'Enthusiasm', rug=FALSE, style="stacked", xlab="Participant expresses enthusiasm", ylab="Probabilities for Each Condition")

Code-wise Logistic Regression

What if we set up a separate model for each of our codes of interest, predicted by the two (interacting) condition variables?

Since were running multiple separate models to test a family of hypotheses on the same data set, well need to perform some correction for multiple comparisons. Here, well use the Benjamini-Hochberg procedure.

Question

mod.Question <- glm(outvis.recode$Question ~ outvis.recode$Model * outvis.recode$Viz, family="binomial")
# compare against the null model
null.Question <- glm(outvis.recode$Question ~ 1, family="binomial")
anova(null.Question, mod.Question, test = "Chisq")
Analysis of Deviance Table

Interpretation

After the BH correction, only two of these models/codes are significant: for Suggestion and for Preferred.
